Sure, I'd be happy to help with that! You can use the `display: flex;` property along with `justify-content: flex-end;` to align a row of divs to the right. Here's a simple example:

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end;
}

.box {
  width: 50px;
  height: 50px;
  background-color: #4caf50;
  margin: 10px;
}
```

In this example, `.container` is the flex container and `.box` are the flex items (the divs). The `justify-content: flex-end;` property aligns the flex items to the end of the container, which in this case is the right side because we read from left to right. The `margin: 10px;` is just for spacing between the boxes. You can adjust the width, height, and background color to fit your needs.
